iimmediately locate the site. It first sends the address to a DNS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iserver, which then queries other servers layer by layer until reaching		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe root servers to obtain the website's IP address. Only then can the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibrowser establish a connection.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThis process repeats every time you visit a new website, resulting in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
islow speeds. Additionally, DNS servers operated by Chinese telecom		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iproviders may hijack your requests to redirect you to pages like 114		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNavigation.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTo accelerate browsing and gain anti-interference benefits, we can set		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iup a local DNS server on our computer. For Linux and Mac systems,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPdnsd is a lightweight solution. It queries other DNS servers via TCP		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior UDP to resolve domain names, caches the results, and significantly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ispeeds up subsequent requests.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
